{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 On monomorphisms and epimorphisms\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Failing the mono/epi condition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Example of failing the monomorphism definition for a non-injection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Monomorphism definition:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\text\{$f : A \\to B$ is a monomorphism\}
\\\\ \\Leftrightarrow \\\\
\\forall Z \\in \\text\{Obj\}(\\mathcal\{C\}), \\;
\\forall g_1, g_2 \\in \\text\{Hom\}(Z, A), \\;
(f \\circ g_1 = f \\circ g_2 \\Rightarrow g_1 = g_2)$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\} {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2\} {\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i x},\u8198?{\i y}\} {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i c},\u8198?2)\}, not injective\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?{\i c})\} {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?{\i b}),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?{\i c})\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?2)\}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The multiple choice of elements (here, {\i a} and {\i b}) in {\i A} which map to 1 in {\i B} is precisely what allows the overall composition to be equal, even when {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}. This provides insight into a proof of "{\i f} is a monomorphism implies that {\i f} is an injection". If you suppose that {\i f} is a monomorphism and not an injection, you can easily reach a contradiction, since you can use elements like 1 and 2 that both map to the same {\i a} to construct a counter-example to the implication that defines a monomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Example of failing the epimorphism definition for a non-surjection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Epimorphism definition:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$\\text\{$f : A \\to B$ is an epimorphism\}
\\\\ \\Leftrightarrow \\\\ 
\\forall Z \\in \\text\{Obj\}(\\mathcal\{C\}), \\;
\\forall g_1, g_2 \\in \\text\{Hom\}(B, Z), \\;
(g_1 \\circ f = g_2 \\circ f \\Rightarrow g_1 = g_2)$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?{\i a}),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?{\i c})\} {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?{\i b}),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?{\i c})\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i x},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i y},\u8198?2)\}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i Z}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\} {\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\} {\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i x},\u8198?{\i y}\} {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?2)\}, not surjective\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i x}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i y}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i x})\} {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i x}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i y}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i y})\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?{\i x}),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?{\i y})\}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The element 3 in {\i B} not being reached by {\i f} is precisely that which provides the opportunity to build {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2} such that they compose to the same result with {\i f}, since the output of 3 for them doesn\u8217't affect the overall composition. This provides insight into a proof of "{\i f} is an epimorphism implies that {\i f} is a surjection". If you suppose that {\i f} is an epimorphism and not a surjection, you can easily reach a contradiction, since you can use elements like 3 that are not reached by {\i f} to construct a counter-example to the implication that defines an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Proofs of mono/inj and epi/surj equivalence\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i f}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i B}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The parts which are "Injection => Monomorphism" and "Surjection => Epimorphism" both use the respective sided inverses to prove the implication.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The other parts use the following tautology to prove the implication by contradiction. "Suppose that {\i p} and \u172?{\i q}, show that it leads to a contradiction".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ({\i p}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i q})\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?((\u172?{\i p})\u8197?\u8746?\u8197?{\i q})\u8196?\u8660?\u8196?(\u172?({\i p}\u8197?\u8745?\u8197?\u172?{\i q}))\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Injection => Monomorphism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i f} is an injection. It thus has post-inverses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8707?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i g}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i A}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 From there:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Obj(\u55349?\u56478?),\u8197?\u8704?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Hom({\i Z},\u8198?{\i A}), $$\\begin\{array\}\{ccccc\} \\\\
f \\circ a = f \\circ b & \\Rightarrow &  g \\circ (f  \\circ a) &=&  g \\circ (f  \\circ b) \\\\
                      & =           & (g \\circ  f) \\circ a  &=& (g \\circ  f) \\circ b  \\\\
                      & =           &         id_A \\circ a  &=&         id_A \\circ b  \\\\
                      & =           &                    a  &=&                    b
\\end\{array\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We conclude that {\i f} is also a monomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Surjection => Epimorphism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i f} is a surjection. It thus has pre-inverses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8707?{\i g}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i B}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i A}),\u8198?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i i}{\i d}{\sub {\i B}}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 From there:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Obj(\u55349?\u56478?),\u8197?\u8704?{\i a},\u8198?{\i b}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Hom({\i B},\u8198?{\i Z}), $$\\begin\{array\}\{ccccc\} \\\\
a \\circ f = b \\circ f & \\Rightarrow & (a \\circ  f) \\circ g  &=& (b \\circ  f) \\circ g  \\\\
                      & =           &  a \\circ (f  \\circ g) &=&  b \\circ (f  \\circ g) \\\\
                      & =           &  a \\circ  id_B        &=&  b \\circ  id_B        \\\\
                      & =           &  a                    &=&  b
\\end\{array\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We conclude that {\i f} is also an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Monomorphism => Injection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i f} is a monomorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Obj(\u55349?\u56478?),\u8197?\u8704?{\i g}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Hom({\i Z},\u8198?{\i A}),\u8197?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose now that {\i f} is not an injection. Algebraically, this means that:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8707?({\i x},\u8198?{\i y})\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i A}{\super 2},\u8198? such that {\i x}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i y} and {\i f}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i y})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can construct {\i g}{\sub 1} and {\i g}{\sub 2} such that {\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2} but {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}, using such a pair ({\i x},\u8198?{\i y}). Thereby, we prove that {\i f} is not an monomorphism and arrive at a contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (If {\i Z} is the empty set, being initial in {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, there is only 1 map into {\i A} (the empty map) and {\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b} always hold. Therefore, any counterexample to the epimorphism definition needs to have at least 1 element.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a}\}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}({\i a})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i x} {\i g}{\sub 2}({\i a})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i y}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Clearly, {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}. However, we also have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i f}({\i g}{\sub 1}({\i a}))\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i x})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i y})\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}({\i g}{\sub 2}({\i a}))\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i f}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 2}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that {\i f} is not a monomorphism: contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: {\i f} is an injection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs20 Epimorphism => Surjection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose that {\i f} is an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8704?{\i Z}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Obj(\u55349?\u56478?),\u8197?\u8704?{\i g}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?Hom({\i B},\u8198?{\i Z}),\u8197?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?\u8658?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Suppose now that {\i f} isn\u8217't a surjection. Algebraically, this means that:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8707?{\i x}\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i B},\u8198?{\i x}\u8196?\u8713?\u8196?{\i f}({\i A})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can construct {\i g}{\sub 1} and {\i g}{\sub 2} such that {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f} but {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}, using such an {\i x}\u8196?\u8713?\u8196?{\i f}({\i A}). Thereby, we prove that {\i f} is not an epimorphism and arrive at a contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (If {\i Z} is the singleton set, being terminal in {\b S}{\b e}{\b t}, there is only 1 map into {\i Z} and {\i a}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i b} always hold. Therefore, any counterexample to the epimorphism definition needs to have at least 2 elements. We will however use a 3-element set, since it makes things more intuitive and pedagogical.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Let {\i Z}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$g_1 =
\\begin\{cases\}
    \\forall x    \\in f(A), g_1(x) = a \\\\
    \\forall x \\notin f(A), g_1(x) = b
\\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 $$g_2 =
\\begin\{cases\}
    \\forall x    \\in f(A), g_2(x) = a \\\\
    \\forall x \\notin f(A), g_2(x) = c
\\end\{cases\}$$\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Clearly, {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}. However, since {\i A} is the domain of {\i f}, of {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}, and of {\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}, we have:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i g}{\sub 1}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i g}{\sub 2}\u8197?\u8728?\u8197?{\i f}\u8196?=\u8196?({\i x}\u8196?\u8614?\u8196?{\i a})\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?({\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z})\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This means that {\i f} is not an epimorphism: contradiction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Conclusion: {\i f} is a surjection.\par}
