{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Another example, this time in a coslice category, with {\i A}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i a},\u8198?{\i b},\u8198?{\i c}\}, we take $\\text\{\\textbf\{Set\}\}_A$. We take {\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{1,\u8198?2,\u8198?3\}, {\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{{\i T},\u8198?{\i F}\}. For {\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?1),\u8198?({\i c},\u8198?3)\} and {\i \u966?}{\sub 2}\u8196?:\u8196?{\i A}\u8196?\u8594?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?\{({\i a},\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?({\i b},\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?({\i c},\u8198?{\i F})\} there exists two elements in {\i H}{\i o}{\i m}{\sub \u55349?\u56494?\u8495?\u55349?\u56521?{\super {\i A}}}({\i Z}{\sub 1},\u8198?{\i Z}{\sub 2}). These originate from two functions in {\b Set}: {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i F})\} and {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u946?}}\u8196?=\u8196?\{(1,\u8198?{\i T}),\u8198?(2,\u8198?{\i F}),\u8198?(3,\u8198?{\i F})\}. The free element in 2\u8196?\u8712?\u8196?{\i Z}{\sub 1} which is not in Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1}) offers a degree of freedom.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Explanations on the conditions for {\i \u963?}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the first example, what causes the issue is the fact that the images of {\i f}{\sub 1} and {\i f}{\sub 2} in {\i A} are distinct.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the second example, what causes the issue is the fact that we\u8217've reduced our common domain {\i A} to an insufficient intermediary object {\i Z}{\sub 1}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "element which isn\u8217't mapped to offers a degree of freedom and thus breaks unicity" in the last example should remind you of the notes on surjections. Indeed, when comparing {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}} and {\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u946?}}, we\u8217're in a context which is reminiscent of the definition of an epimorphism.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i \u966?}{\sub 2}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}{\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\u8196?=\u8196?{\i \u963?}{\sub {\i \u945?}}{\i \u966?}{\sub 1}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We can be assured of being able to cancel {\i \u966?}1 iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 1} is an epimorphism, and thus {\i \u963?}, if it exists, is unique. The proof for slice categories is similar, but given the reverse orders, uses monomorphisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 More generally:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a) in a slice category, there will be no {\i \u963?} if Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 2}) (proof ? and in more general categories than concrete categories ? TODO: iff ?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab b) in a coslice category, there will be no {\i \u963?} if Pr(Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 1})\u8196?\u8800?\u8196?Pr(Im({\i \u966?}{\sub 2})) (proof ? and in more general categories than concrete categories ? TODO: iff ?)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab c) in a slice category, there is at most a single {\i \u963?} iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 2} is mono\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab d) in a coslice category, there is at most a single {\i \u963?} iff {\i \u966?}{\sub 1} is epi\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (see perhaps https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/over+category and https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/under+category )\par}
