{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Initial and terminal objects\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab there are categories without either initial or terminal objects, such as the preorder category of \u8484? with \u8804?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab there are categories with multiple initial or terminal objects (for example, in {\b Set}, every singleton set is a terminal object); however, these are respectively unique up to isomorphism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab any object which is both initial and terminal is called a zero object.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Universal properties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 "Normal" universal properties\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Verbatim: "The most natural context in which to introduce universal properties requires a good familiarity with the language of functors, which we will only introduce at a later stage. [...] We say that a construction satis\u64257?es a universal property (or: \u8217'is the solution to a universal problem\u8217') when it may be viewed as a terminal object of a category."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then: "The declaration/explanation of a universal property generally follows the pattern \u8217'object X is universal with respect to the following property: for any Y such that..., there exists a unique morphism Y \u8594? X such that...\u8217'; this explanation hides the de\u64257?nition of an accessory category, and the statement that X is terminal."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a complicated way to say: there is some construct to decompose a morphism which is "universal" (always exists) and reduces the rest of the information of the morphism into something "unique" (hence terminal object of some subcategory).\par}
